<p align="center">
  <b>Success Criteria</b>
</p>

Our main goal for this iteration is to ensure the gear rotation system for gas dispersion is effective and durable. A successful prototype demonstrates the ability to move the nozzle in a periodic sweeping motion to achieve adequate gas dispersion across the vines.

| Criterion | What It Assesses | Measurement Method |
|-----------|------------------|--------------------|
| After continuous testing for over 1 minute with gears spinning at least 90°, all gears spin without interference or skipping | Long-term gear reliability across multiple harvests | Observe gear mesh through 20+ cycles at 20 RPM; record any skipping or interference events |
| After continuous testing for over 1 minute with gears spinning at least 90°, all parts remain structurally intact | Structural durability to avoid ongoing farmer maintenance | Inspect all joints, fasteners, and the base after 20+ cycles for loosening, cracking, or detachment |
| Nozzle achieves an approximate 90° range of motion without significant resistance | Effective gas dispersion sweep across the vine rows | Measure angular range of nozzle travel; confirm smooth rotation with no notable friction or resistance |

**Exhibit Demo:** Upon spinning the handle, the nozzle rotates through a 90° arc driven by the spur gear system — directly demonstrating the range-of-motion and smoothness criteria in a single visible action.
